frameDefinitions: The words in this frame refer to what Clothing the Wearer (or a specific Body_part of the Wearer) has on.
A Wearer removes an item of Clothing from a Body_location (the part of the body that the Clothing is prototypically worn on.)
The Subparts of Clothing items worn by a Wearer and made of a certain Material.
This frame refers to clothing and its characteristics,  including anything that people conventionally wear.
The words in this frame describe the manipulation of an Entity by an Agent.
A Figure is located in contact with a Ground.
frameExamples: I <t>had</t> <t>on</t> the most ridiculous monkey-suit you could imagine.
Walking on sand is better if you <t>take</t> <t>off</t> your shoes. INI
The shirt features a long <t>sleeve</t> with shiny gold buttons.
Claudia dressed in a dark green cotton <t>DRESS</t> clasped round her slender waist with a broad yellow belt , drank a cup of coffee and opened her neglected post .
There was a tight-fitting lid <t>on</t> the bottle .
listRoleDefinitions: The person whose clothing is under discussion.
This role identifies the <fen>Clothing</fen> that the <fen>Wearer</fen> wears.
The body part of the <fen>Wearer</fen> which is covered by the <fen>Clothing</fen>.
The time at or during which the <fen>Wearer</fen> has the <fen>Clothing</fen> on.
The individual who begins the action wearing the <fen>Clothing</fen> and ends the action without it.
The item that the <fen>Wearer</fen> is initially wearing but then removes.
The location at which the <fen>Wearer</fen> undresses an item of <fen>Clothing</fen>.
This is a <fen>Subpart</fen> of the <fen>Clothing</fen> item.
This role identifes the clothing worn.

The <fen>Agent</fen> manipulates an object. <fen>Agent</fen> typically refers to animate beings, but is also extended to mechanical and other inanimate objects.  <fen>Agent</fen> is most frequently expressed as the external argument of verbs:
The <fen>Entity</fen> being manipulated often occurs as the direct object of verbs:

The part of the <fen>Agent</fen>'s body being used to manipulate the <fen>Entity</fen> may also be expressed. While the default is for an <fen>Agent</fen> to use his/her hands, other body parts may be specified. This frame element usually occurs as a PP-complement.
The spatial setting in which the manipulation takes place.
The <fen>Ground</fen> serves as a basis for describing the location of the <fen>Figure</fen>.
The <fen>Figure</fen> is perceived as located relative to a certain <fen>Ground</fen> location. The figure can be an entity or an event.
The <fen>Figures</fen> are items which mutually serve to identify the location of each other.
The period of time during which the locative relation between <fen>Figure</fen> and <fen>Ground</fen> obtains.
